## Pattern

👉 Heap / Priority Queue

---

## Recognition Trigger

Look for phrases like:

```text
kth largest
kth smallest
top k
largest k elements
smallest k elements
```

These should immediately make you think:

```text
Heap
```

---

# Your Solution

```cpp
priority_queue<int> pq;

for (auto it : nums)
    pq.push(it);

for (int i = 0; i < k; i++) {
    res = pq.top();
    pq.pop();
}

return res;
```

---

## Key Insight

A max heap always keeps:

```text
largest element at the top
```

Example:

```text
nums = [3,2,1,5,6,4]
k = 2
```

Heap:

```text
top = 6
```

Pop once:

```text
6 removed
```

New top:

```text
5
```

That's the 2nd largest.

---

# Complexity

### Building heap

```text
O(n log n)
```

(using repeated pushes)

### Removing k elements

```text
O(k log n)
```

Total:

```text
O(n log n)
```

Space:

```text
O(n)
```

---

# Better Heap Solution

Instead of storing all elements:

Use a **min heap of size k**.

---

## Idea

Keep only the largest k elements seen so far.

```cpp
priority_queue<
    int,
    vector<int>,
    greater<int>
> pq;
```

---

Example:

```text
nums = [3,2,1,5,6,4]
k = 2
```

Process:

```text
3 -> [3]
2 -> [2,3]
1 -> ignore (heap grows to 3 then pop smallest)

5 -> [3,5]
6 -> [5,6]
4 -> [5,6]
```

Top:

```text
5
```

which is the 2nd largest.

---

## Complexity

Time:

```text
O(n log k)
```

Space:

```text
O(k)
```

This is usually the expected heap solution.

---

# Best Possible Solution

There's also:

```text
Quick Select
```

Pattern:

```text
Partitioning (same idea as Quick Sort)
```

Average:

```text
O(n)
```

Worst:

```text
O(n²)
```

Interviewers sometimes expect this if they ask:

```text
Can you do better than O(n log n)?
```

